'...America...

47
00:05:22,973 --> 00:05:25,441
'...might save my hide.

48
00:05:28,093 --> 00:05:29,606
''Either way...

49
00:05:30,493 --> 00:05:32,006
''...I am ready...

50
00:05:32,653 --> 00:05:33,927
''...for what...

51
00:05:34,333 --> 00:05:35,686
''...comes.

52
00:05:37,133 --> 00:05:39,203
''The Irish Republic...

53
00:05:41,133 --> 00:05:42,725
''...is a dream...

54
00:05:43,053 --> 00:05:44,247
''...no longer. ''

55
00:05:44,333 --> 00:05:45,288
Fire!

56
00:05:48,413 --> 00:05:50,324
'lt is daily sealed...

57
00:05:52,413 --> 00:05:54,563
'...by the lifeblood...

58
00:05:55,293 --> 00:05:57,204
'...of those who...

59
00:05:58,093 --> 00:05:59,924
'...proclaimed it.

60
00:06:07,293 --> 00:06:09,523
'And every one of us...

61
00:06:10,893 --> 00:06:12,246
'...they shoot...

62
00:06:13,933 --> 00:06:16,401
''...brings more people...

63
00:06:17,853 --> 00:06:19,684
''...to our side.

64
00:06:22,573 --> 00:06:24,484
''They cannot imprison us...

65
00:06:24,813 --> 00:06:26,087
''...forever.

66
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:28,566
''And from...

67
00:06:28,973 --> 00:06:30,167
''...the day...

68
00:06:30,493 --> 00:06:32,165
''...of our release...

69
00:06:33,213 --> 00:06:34,407
''...Michael...

70
00:06:35,773 --> 00:06:37,365
''...we must act...

71
00:06:38,093 --> 00:06:40,004
''...as if the Republic...

72
00:06:40,333 --> 00:06:41,288
''...is...

73
00:06:41,453 --> 00:06:42,966
''...a fact.

74
00:06:43,773 --> 00:06:45,365
'We defeat...

75
00:06:46,893 --> 00:06:48,485
'...the British Empire...

76
00:06:50,093 --> 00:06:51,367
'...by...

77
00:06:53,053 --> 00:06:54,327
'...ignoring it.'

78
00:07:18,253 --> 00:07:22,007
They let us out of jail so we can
do our best to be put inside again.

79
00:07:25,693 --> 00:07:28,082
Don't you see a certain paradox in that?

80
00:07:30,493 --> 00:07:31,926
Paradox.

81
00:07:32,093 --> 00:07:33,606
A contradiction.

82
00:07:34,573 --> 00:07:38,327
An immovable force meets an
immovable object kind of thing.

83
00:08:07,533 --> 00:08:09,922
Look, isn't that a lovely picture?

84
00:08:12,573 --> 00:08:14,404
Maybe we should settle down.

85
00:08:14,493 --> 00:08:16,085
Just the two of us?

86
00:08:16,253 --> 00:08:17,288
And him.

87
00:08:18,413 --> 00:08:19,368
Who?

88
00:08:25,133 --> 00:08:26,327
How are you?

89
00:08:26,493 --> 00:08:28,324
How long has that man been there?

90
00:08:28,413 --> 00:08:31,052
As long as we have. Half an hour or so.

91
00:08:33,133 --> 00:08:34,566
How'd they know we were coming?

92
00:08:34,653 --> 00:08:36,245
They know what we ate for breakfast.

93
00:08:36,333 --> 00:08:38,722
There's only one way to beat them, then.

94
00:08:38,813 --> 00:08:41,043
Find out what they eat for breakfast.

95
00:08:46,973 --> 00:08:47,849
Fuck.

96
00:08:48,013 --> 00:08:49,446
lt's market day.

97
00:08:52,533 --> 00:08:54,012
Where are you going?

98
00:08:58,893 --> 00:09:00,963
So, what did you have for breakfast?

99
00:09:01,053 --> 00:09:03,931
A traffic jam, lads.
lf you backed up, we could back up...

100
00:09:04,013 --> 00:09:05,844
...and you could chase us some more.

101
00:09:05,933 --> 00:09:08,652
lf we sit here a minute, it'll sort itself out.

102
00:09:08,813 --> 00:09:10,166
Grand so.

103
00:09:24,653 --> 00:09:27,770
The fact that the candidate
you're being asked to vote for...

104
00:09:27,853 --> 00:09:31,766
...is at this moment rotting in an
English jail shouldn't put you off!

105
00:09:32,013 --> 00:09:34,732
l was in one myself till a week ago!

106
00:09:35,933 --> 00:09:37,446
They can jail us.

107
00:09:37,613 --> 00:09:38,966
They can shoot us.

108
00:09:39,853 --> 00:09:41,923
They can even conscript us!

109
00:09:42,733 --> 00:09:46,169
They can use us as cannon
fodder in the Somme!

110
00:09:47,693 --> 00:09:48,808
But...

111
00:09:48,973 --> 00:09:51,282
...we have a weapon more powerful...

112
00:09:51,453 --> 00:09:54,889
...than any in the whole
arsenal of the British Empire!

113
00:09:55,053 --> 00:09:56,247
That weapon...

114
00:09:56,333 --> 00:09:58,244
...is our refusal!

115
00:09:59,053 --> 00:10:02,489
Our refusal to bow to
any order but our own!

116
00:10:03,213 --> 00:10:05,602
Any institution but our own!

117
00:10:08,733 --> 00:10:12,487
Our friends in the Royal lrish
Constabulary want to shut me up.

118
00:10:14,333 --> 00:10:16,972
Jail me again, shoot me, who knows?

119
00:10:17,693 --> 00:10:20,253
But l'd like you to send them a message!

120
00:10:20,573 --> 00:10:23,531
lf they shut me up,
who'll take my place?

121
00:10:25,213 --> 00:10:26,646
Who'll take my place?

122
00:10:26,733 --> 00:10:28,246
We will!

123
00:10:28,493 --> 00:10:31,212
l can't hear you! Who'll take my place?

124
00:10:31,613 --> 00:10:33,604
Will they shut you up?

125
00:10:42,493 --> 00:10:43,528
Clear a path!

126
00:10:43,613 --> 00:10:44,887
Clear a path!

127
00:10:45,053 --> 00:10:47,408
Get him out! Go, get him out!

128
00:10:59,693 --> 00:11:01,524
So, what's your name?

129
00:11:01,693 --> 00:11:02,648
Kitty.

130
00:11:03,533 --> 00:11:04,807
ls Harry here?

131
00:11:04,973 --> 00:11:06,565
Downstairs.

132
00:11:07,853 --> 00:11:09,764
What did they hit you with?

133
00:11:09,933 --> 00:11:11,924
Whatever it was, it was hard.

134
00:11:16,253 --> 00:11:18,483
-You'll be all right.
-You're a nurse, Kitty?

135
00:11:18,573 --> 00:11:19,688
l'm nothing.

136
00:11:20,333 --> 00:11:22,005
l'm my father's daughter.

137
00:11:22,173 --> 00:11:23,208
Who's your father?

138
00:11:23,293 --> 00:11:24,408
He's dead.

139
00:11:26,173 --> 00:11:28,971
There's dinner in an hour,
if you fancy it.

140
00:11:29,213 --> 00:11:30,407
Grand so.

141
00:11:31,853 --> 00:11:34,811
'Last night she came to me

142
00:11:35,453 --> 00:11:38,092
'She came softly in

143
00:11:39,933 --> 00:11:42,572
'Was so softly she came that

144
00:11:44,013 --> 00:11:46,573
'Her feet made no din

145
00:11:48,253 --> 00:11:50,972
'And she laid her hand on me

146
00:11:52,173 --> 00:11:54,733
'And this she did say

147
00:11:56,253 --> 00:11:59,484
''Aye, it will not be long, love

148
00:12:01,213 --> 00:12:02,726
''Till our

149
00:12:02,893 --> 00:12:04,804
''Wedding day''

150
00:12:07,053 --> 00:12:09,123
Gorgeous, Kitty. Beautiful.

151
00:12:11,373 --> 00:12:13,364
Mick's about to make another speech.

152
00:12:13,453 --> 00:12:16,331
What are you saying, you Dublin jackeen?

153
00:12:16,493 --> 00:12:17,767
What would you know about singing?

154
00:12:17,853 --> 00:12:20,572
l agree, you West Cork muck savage.

155
00:12:20,733 --> 00:12:22,325
You're the expert in singing.

156
00:12:22,413 --> 00:12:23,482
So it's your turn now, right?

157
00:12:23,573 --> 00:12:25,529
Hey, hey, give over, Harry, will ya.

158
00:12:25,613 --> 00:12:28,173
She has a voice like an angel.
l have one like a puck goat.

159
00:12:28,253 --> 00:12:30,164
ls it or is it not Mick's turn?

160
00:12:30,253 --> 00:12:31,368
No, please.

161
00:12:31,853 --> 00:12:33,684
A noble call is mine...

162
00:12:33,853 --> 00:12:36,321
...and l call on Michael.

163
00:12:36,493 --> 00:12:38,882
Mick, give us your party piece.

164
00:12:39,213 --> 00:12:41,283
Come on, Mick. Give us a song.

165
00:12:41,453 --> 00:12:43,125
He hasn't a note in his head.

166
00:12:43,213 --> 00:12:44,168
Shut up.

167
00:12:47,133 --> 00:12:50,569
'Well do l remember
the bleak December day

168
00:12:50,733 --> 00:12:53,725
'The landlord and the sheriff
came to drive us all away

169
00:12:54,253 --> 00:12:57,928
'They set my roof on fire with
their cursed foreign spleen

170
00:12:58,253 --> 00:13:00,813
'And that's another reason

171
00:13:00,973 --> 00:13:04,010
'Why l left old Skibereen'

172
00:13:05,053 --> 00:13:06,691
Twelve more verses, now.

173
00:13:27,053 --> 00:13:28,805
You wanted to be woken.

174
00:13:29,133 --> 00:13:33,365
There was a man in West Cork
who proposed to five sisters...

175
00:13:34,333 --> 00:13:35,925
...one after the other.

176
00:13:36,573 --> 00:13:38,404
l suppose they all refused.

177
00:13:38,573 --> 00:13:41,531
Then the father died,
and he proposed to the mother.

178
00:13:42,973 --> 00:13:45,123
Are you trying to tell me something?

179
00:13:45,453 --> 00:13:48,092
l was building up to a proposal.

180
00:13:48,253 --> 00:13:50,721
lt's not easy with a Fenian in your bed.

181
00:13:52,653 --> 00:13:54,325
-He likes you too.
-l do?

182
00:13:54,493 --> 00:13:55,448
Stop it.

183
00:13:55,533 --> 00:13:57,603
-But, sadly, he snores.
-l do not.

184
00:13:57,693 --> 00:13:59,365
So it's up to you, Kitty.

185
00:14:00,333 --> 00:14:03,450
-l don't have to like either.
-Never was a truer word spoken.

186
00:14:03,533 --> 00:14:05,603
And he sleeps in his trousers.

187
00:14:07,773 --> 00:14:09,365
Forgive the brute.

188
00:14:10,253 --> 00:14:11,129
Morning.

189
00:14:11,213 --> 00:14:12,202
Morning.

190
00:14:12,493 --> 00:14:13,767
Behave yourself.

191
00:14:13,933 --> 00:14:15,207
Am l dreaming?

192
00:14:15,373 --> 00:14:16,647
l think you are.

193
00:14:20,333 --> 00:14:21,527
We'll be an invisible army.

194
00:14:21,613 --> 00:14:25,049
Our uniform will be that of the man
on the street, the peasant in the field.

195
00:14:25,133 --> 00:14:28,330
We'll strike the enemy
and vanish back in the crowd again.

196
00:14:28,493 --> 00:14:30,006
What do we strike with?

197
00:14:30,093 --> 00:14:31,492
What have you got?

198
00:14:34,733 --> 00:14:35,688
Show me.

199
00:14:35,853 --> 00:14:37,684
Jeez, look at this, Harry.

200
00:14:37,933 --> 00:14:40,242
Same old story.
You need something better.

201
00:14:40,333 --> 00:14:41,846
Where's the police barracks?

202
00:14:41,933 --> 00:14:44,652
-Two miles down the road.
-There is an arsenal.

203
00:14:44,813 --> 00:14:46,804
How do we get in? We have no bullets!

204
00:14:46,893 --> 00:14:48,406
They don't know that.

205
00:14:49,853 --> 00:14:51,002
What's that?

206
00:14:52,173 --> 00:14:54,641
-A sod of turf.
-Wrong. That's a weapon.

207
00:14:55,213 --> 00:14:56,248
Fucking deadly.

208
00:14:56,333 --> 00:14:57,846
You don't believe me?

209
00:15:04,253 --> 00:15:05,686
What is it now?

210
00:15:30,253 --> 00:15:31,686
Good evening, lads.

211
00:15:32,093 --> 00:15:33,446
Hands in the air.

212
00:15:33,533 --> 00:15:35,171
-Drop your weapons!
-Now!

213
00:15:38,813 --> 00:15:41,611
We'll relieve you of your responsibilities.

214
00:15:45,533 --> 00:15:47,364
Grab that bag, one of youse.

215
00:15:50,013 --> 00:15:52,322
Jesus, lads, it's Christmas.

216
00:15:57,213 --> 00:15:59,602
You'll be organized in flying columns.

217
00:15:59,773 --> 00:16:02,207
Fight on your own terms.
What's your name?

218
00:16:02,413 --> 00:16:03,846
-Whose terms, Pat?
-Ours.

219
00:16:03,933 --> 00:16:06,242
l want each of those to capture ten more.

220
00:16:06,333 --> 00:16:09,370
And l want you to account for every bullet,
understand?

221
00:16:09,613 --> 00:16:10,728
Stand up!

222
00:16:12,333 --> 00:16:14,164
-You understand?
-Yes, sir!

223
00:16:14,413 --> 00:16:17,883
l'll make a fucking army out of you
if it's the last thing l do.

224
00:16:26,813 --> 00:16:28,485
-Am l late, Joe?
-Not yet.

225
00:16:28,573 --> 00:16:30,643
Can't keep the gob-shites waiting.

226
00:16:40,613 --> 00:16:42,012
Harry, l want something--

227
00:16:42,093 --> 00:16:44,288
Hold on, hold on. Behind you.

228
00:16:46,413 --> 00:16:48,005
Jesus wept.

229
00:16:51,653 --> 00:16:53,132
Five minutes.

230
00:17:00,333 --> 00:17:01,652
Sit down.

231
00:17:01,933 --> 00:17:03,161
Have a drink.

232
00:17:11,853 --> 00:17:13,252
What's this?

233
00:17:13,413 --> 00:17:14,687
What's all this?

234
00:17:15,373 --> 00:17:17,329
You've been on my heels for weeks.

235
00:17:17,413 --> 00:17:19,051
Very eager for a G man.

236
00:17:20,333 --> 00:17:22,051
l've something for you.

237
00:17:22,573 --> 00:17:23,722
Don't!

238
00:17:23,853 --> 00:17:25,889
Don't you ever calm down?

239
00:17:28,773 --> 00:17:30,968
Names and addresses
of the whole cabinet.

240
00:17:31,053 --> 00:17:32,930
They're to be lifted tonight.

241
00:17:35,253 --> 00:17:37,084
lt's an illegal gathering...

242
00:17:37,173 --> 00:17:39,846
...in open defiance
of His Majesty's government.

243
00:17:45,813 --> 00:17:47,246
How'd you get this?

244
00:17:47,853 --> 00:17:50,686
Like you said, l'm eager, for a G man.

245
00:17:52,453 --> 00:17:54,250
Why should l trust you?

246
00:17:54,453 --> 00:17:56,603
Logically, l suppose you shouldn't.

247
00:17:57,253 --> 00:17:59,813
But l've been on your heels for weeks...

248
00:18:00,013 --> 00:18:02,243
...making notes of your speeches.

249
00:18:03,493 --> 00:18:06,212
Let's just say that you can be persuasive.

250
00:18:09,613 --> 00:18:11,490
You work for the Castle.

251
00:18:11,653 --> 00:18:12,802
l know.

252
00:18:13,733 --> 00:18:15,371
What was it you said...

253
00:18:15,853 --> 00:18:18,208
...'Our only weapon is our refusal.'

254
00:18:30,853 --> 00:18:33,242
l am getting very tired of the spectacle...

255
00:18:33,333 --> 00:18:36,689
...of an upstart dominating
these entire cabinet proceedings.

256
00:18:36,813 --> 00:18:38,929
l've said it before and l'll say it again:

257
00:18:39,013 --> 00:18:41,971
The minister is, as usual,
exceeding his brief.

258
00:18:42,093 --> 00:18:43,606
And just what is my brief?

259
00:18:43,693 --> 00:18:45,092
lntelligence.

260
00:18:45,253 --> 00:18:46,288
Bullshit.

261
00:18:46,413 --> 00:18:49,849
l'm minister for gunrunning,
daylight robbery and general mayhem.

262
00:18:49,933 --> 00:18:52,606
Until we're armed,
nothing's going to happen.

263
00:18:52,813 --> 00:18:55,964
But as minister of intelligence,
l'd like to inform you...

264
00:18:56,133 --> 00:18:58,408
...that each of us is to be arrested...

265
00:18:58,573 --> 00:18:59,642
...tonight.

266
00:19:01,573 --> 00:19:03,291
How does the minister know this?

267
00:19:03,373 --> 00:19:05,762
Now, Cathal, don't exceed your brief.

268
00:19:07,173 --> 00:19:11,246
Names, addresses, next of kin,
of the whole cabinet.

269
00:19:12,933 --> 00:19:15,572
They know more about us
than our mothers do.

270
00:19:16,453 --> 00:19:18,250
How do we know it's genuine?

271
00:19:18,933 --> 00:19:21,242
We don't, chief. But it could well be.

