01:02:19,733 --> 01:02:22,088
l'm not his bloody wife!

815
01:02:32,723 --> 01:02:34,202
Say your prayers.

816
01:02:37,723 --> 01:02:39,600
You know what it says, Kitty?

817
01:02:40,603 --> 01:02:44,118
lt says, 'Give us the future.
We've had enough of your past.'

818
01:02:44,443 --> 01:02:45,956
The Lord is my shepherd....

819
01:02:46,043 --> 01:02:47,874
''Give us our country back...

820
01:02:48,603 --> 01:02:49,956
''...to live in...

821
01:02:50,043 --> 01:02:51,396
''...to grow in...

822
01:02:52,283 --> 01:02:53,477
''...to love. ''

823
01:03:03,203 --> 01:03:05,512
So there is love there, Mick.

824
01:03:23,363 --> 01:03:24,842
Hang on, Rosie.

825
01:03:30,363 --> 01:03:32,513
Clean sheets, l think.

826
01:03:39,443 --> 01:03:40,717
Come on!

827
01:03:50,483 --> 01:03:51,802
So, Mick...

828
01:03:53,523 --> 01:03:55,115
...flowers delivered.

829
01:03:57,363 --> 01:03:59,115
Do you think they got the message?

830
01:04:13,283 --> 01:04:14,682
Any casualties?

831
01:04:18,363 --> 01:04:19,921
Any casualties?

832
01:04:22,043 --> 01:04:23,317
Are you deaf?

833
01:04:23,483 --> 01:04:24,552
Broy.

834
01:04:24,883 --> 01:04:26,794
Ned - fucking - Broy!

835
01:04:28,083 --> 01:04:30,836
What are you talking about?
Broy wasn't out.

836
01:04:31,163 --> 01:04:32,994
They lifted him at Vaughan's.

837
01:04:36,123 --> 01:04:37,522
What was he doing?

838
01:04:38,483 --> 01:04:40,394
Oh, sweet mother of Jesus.

839
01:07:26,523 --> 01:07:28,479
Can't risk it any longer, Mick.

840
01:07:29,563 --> 01:07:31,281
Who'll give in first, Joe?

841
01:07:31,443 --> 01:07:32,717
Us or them?

842
01:07:34,523 --> 01:07:36,241
The body or the lash?

843
01:07:51,323 --> 01:07:53,075
You look like a gangster!

844
01:07:53,603 --> 01:07:55,514
You look like a ghost!

845
01:07:56,203 --> 01:07:57,682
Welcome back, Harry!

846
01:07:58,123 --> 01:07:59,442
How are you keeping?

847
01:07:59,523 --> 01:08:00,922
Grand.

848
01:08:03,363 --> 01:08:05,001
You're famous over there.

849
01:08:05,083 --> 01:08:06,152
Where?

850
01:08:06,763 --> 01:08:08,515
Over there, you thick.

851
01:08:09,123 --> 01:08:10,875
So, how was America?

852
01:08:12,283 --> 01:08:13,238
Great.

853
01:08:15,163 --> 01:08:17,393
Dev never got to meet the President.

854
01:08:18,043 --> 01:08:19,681
l didn't think he would.

855
01:08:26,123 --> 01:08:27,272
How are you?

856
01:08:28,163 --> 01:08:29,642
l'm grand.

857
01:08:36,763 --> 01:08:38,242
Welcome back, chief.

858
01:08:45,803 --> 01:08:48,033
The Big Fella sends his regards.

859
01:08:53,403 --> 01:08:55,633
We'll see who is the big fella.

860
01:08:59,483 --> 01:09:00,996
Apologies, gentlemen.

861
01:09:24,283 --> 01:09:26,513
As you may know...

862
01:09:30,043 --> 01:09:34,400
...we have had some communication
from the British side.

863
01:09:35,883 --> 01:09:38,841
There is a slim possibility...

864
01:09:39,963 --> 01:09:42,158
...that they might want to talk.

865
01:09:45,123 --> 01:09:46,522
But our...

866
01:09:48,363 --> 01:09:49,637
...tactics...

867
01:09:51,483 --> 01:09:55,396
...allowed the British press
to paint us as murderers.

868
01:09:57,883 --> 01:10:01,239
lf we are to negotiate
as a legitimate government...

869
01:10:01,363 --> 01:10:03,638
...our armed forces must act...

870
01:10:03,803 --> 01:10:06,237
...like a legitimate army.

871
01:10:09,883 --> 01:10:12,522
What exactly do you mean, Dev?

872
01:10:13,643 --> 01:10:16,441
l mean large-scale engagements.

873
01:10:18,443 --> 01:10:20,559
You mean, like in 1916?

874
01:10:22,203 --> 01:10:24,842
The great heroic ethic of failure...

875
01:10:25,563 --> 01:10:28,236
...marching to slaughter.

876
01:10:29,003 --> 01:10:31,563
Why don't we save them the bother
and blow our own brains out?

877
01:10:31,643 --> 01:10:32,758
How dare you!

878
01:10:32,843 --> 01:10:34,674
How did we get them to this point...

879
01:10:34,763 --> 01:10:36,355
...to consider talking?

880
01:10:36,443 --> 01:10:39,401
We brought them to their knees
the only way we could!

881
01:10:39,483 --> 01:10:41,075
They call us...

882
01:10:41,243 --> 01:10:42,517
...murderers.

883
01:10:42,643 --> 01:10:44,838
War is murder! Sheer, bloody murder!

884
01:10:45,083 --> 01:10:47,961
Had you been here the past year,
you'd know that!

885
01:10:55,323 --> 01:10:57,473
l propose an assault...

886
01:10:57,643 --> 01:11:01,841
...on the administrative center
of British rule in lreland:

887
01:11:07,163 --> 01:11:09,074
The Customs House.

888
01:11:12,843 --> 01:11:15,641
Ashes to ashes, dust to dust.

889
01:11:18,603 --> 01:11:19,718
How many lost?

890
01:11:19,803 --> 01:11:23,159
6 dead, 70 taken! Bloody fiasco!

891
01:11:23,723 --> 01:11:25,236
Christ, not again!

892
01:11:41,563 --> 01:11:42,678
The guns!

893
01:11:42,843 --> 01:11:44,356
We need the guns!

894
01:11:44,523 --> 01:11:45,797
Leave them!

895
01:12:24,283 --> 01:12:26,114
There's nothing we can do.

896
01:12:27,643 --> 01:12:29,361
There's nothing we can do.

897
01:12:31,323 --> 01:12:33,712
How much longer can we hold out?

898
01:12:37,483 --> 01:12:39,838
Four weeks. But keep it a secret.

899
01:12:40,043 --> 01:12:41,556
As little as that?

900
01:12:41,683 --> 01:12:43,514
Unless we use bows and arrows.

901
01:12:43,603 --> 01:12:46,037
Don't be flippant, Michael.

902
01:12:48,603 --> 01:12:50,912
We nearly lost 80 men last week, Dev.

903
01:12:52,523 --> 01:12:54,002
You tell him, Harry.

904
01:13:01,243 --> 01:13:02,642
He's right, chief.

905
01:13:05,603 --> 01:13:07,082
l lied.

906
01:13:07,963 --> 01:13:10,033
You lied? About what?

907
01:13:10,483 --> 01:13:12,917
We can't hold out for another week.

908
01:13:15,283 --> 01:13:17,001
Christ! Do they know that?

909
01:13:17,123 --> 01:13:18,602
Nobody knows.

910
01:13:19,123 --> 01:13:20,954
Mick, Dev's negotiating.

911
01:13:21,123 --> 01:13:23,318
Yes, so he doesn't know either.

912
01:13:23,643 --> 01:13:25,838
lt's very important he doesn't know.

913
01:13:26,123 --> 01:13:28,512
The world must believe we're invincible.

914
01:13:28,643 --> 01:13:30,361
Maybe then we can talk.

915
01:13:32,643 --> 01:13:34,474
Jesus Christ.

916
01:13:37,083 --> 01:13:38,516
Kitty's down.

917
01:13:40,763 --> 01:13:42,162
So l heard.

918
01:13:44,963 --> 01:13:47,636
ls she down to see you or me?

919
01:13:47,803 --> 01:13:49,475
Maybe both of us.

920
01:13:51,003 --> 01:13:53,676
You take her down to Kingstown.
Get some sea air.

921
01:13:53,763 --> 01:13:55,401
No, why don't you take her?

922
01:13:55,483 --> 01:13:57,235
No, you take her.

923
01:13:57,883 --> 01:13:59,874
-No, you take her.
-No, you do.

924
01:14:03,563 --> 01:14:06,760
A horse called 'lrish Republic'
ran at Donnybrook today.

925
01:14:07,003 --> 01:14:08,675
What were the odds?

926
01:14:08,843 --> 01:14:11,641
-50-to-1 .
-Jesus, some odds, what?

927
01:14:13,083 --> 01:14:16,519
There's 100,000 Tommies here
and not 2,000 of us.

928
01:14:16,643 --> 01:14:19,396
l'd say 50-to-1 is optimistic.

929
01:14:19,683 --> 01:14:21,401
Optimistic or no...

930
01:14:21,523 --> 01:14:22,592
...she won.

931
01:14:22,683 --> 01:14:24,116
No, you're joking?

932
01:14:24,923 --> 01:14:27,881
10 bob each way, that makes £25...

933
01:14:28,043 --> 01:14:30,352
...plus the place money, £7,10.

934
01:14:30,523 --> 01:14:31,797
So l won...

935
01:14:31,963 --> 01:14:34,523
...£33,10, thank you very much.

936
01:14:35,243 --> 01:14:37,757
Let the lrish Republic buy us dinner.

937
01:14:37,923 --> 01:14:40,278
l know just where to go.

938
01:14:56,283 --> 01:14:58,592
Which one of you will ask me to dance?

939
01:14:58,763 --> 01:15:00,719
-Me, me, me, please!
-No, l will. l will.

940
01:15:00,803 --> 01:15:03,158
Heads, it's Harry. Tails, it's Mick.

941
01:15:05,883 --> 01:15:09,717
-Kitty, may l have the pleasure?
-The gangster wins again.

942
01:15:09,963 --> 01:15:11,521
Watch his feet, Kitty.

943
01:15:11,643 --> 01:15:12,996
Shut up, you.

944
01:15:16,843 --> 01:15:19,038
l shouldn't have left, should l?

945
01:15:19,203 --> 01:15:20,352
Why not?

946
01:15:21,483 --> 01:15:23,235
l was a length ahead.

947
01:15:23,403 --> 01:15:24,677
Now where am l?

948
01:15:25,163 --> 01:15:26,801
lt's not a race, Harry.

949
01:15:30,363 --> 01:15:32,638
Mind telling me what it is, then?

950
01:15:34,683 --> 01:15:36,116
You without him...

951
01:15:36,323 --> 01:15:37,802
...him without you...

952
01:15:38,403 --> 01:15:39,961
...l can't imagine it.

953
01:15:40,923 --> 01:15:42,595
Three-legged race.

954
01:15:57,243 --> 01:15:59,234
Mick, where the hell have you been?

955
01:15:59,323 --> 01:16:02,759
For God's sake, give me one
free night to be a human being!

956
01:16:02,923 --> 01:16:04,914
We looked all over! Have you heard?

957
01:16:05,003 --> 01:16:06,356
No, l haven't heard!

958
01:16:06,443 --> 01:16:10,277
Would the bloody lrish Republic
leave me some time off?

959
01:16:10,443 --> 01:16:11,717
lt's over!

960
01:16:12,603 --> 01:16:13,922
What's over?

961
01:16:14,203 --> 01:16:15,272
lt's over.

962
01:16:15,563 --> 01:16:17,155
They called a truce.

963
01:16:21,443 --> 01:16:22,671
lt's finished?

964
01:16:22,843 --> 01:16:24,754
-The whole damn thing.
-Yes.

965
01:16:25,803 --> 01:16:27,156
We've won?

966
01:16:27,283 --> 01:16:29,717
Lloyd George has thrown in the towel?

967
01:16:30,763 --> 01:16:34,199
We've brought the British Empire
to its knees?

968
01:16:34,523 --> 01:16:35,478
Yes.

969
01:16:37,083 --> 01:16:39,756
Why the fuck didn't you say so?

970
01:16:46,203 --> 01:16:48,114
What was that horse called?

971
01:16:54,243 --> 01:16:56,473
We did it! We did it! lt's a truce!

972
01:17:14,123 --> 01:17:14,999
What?

973
01:17:16,843 --> 01:17:18,834
You must be joking?

974
01:17:20,523 --> 01:17:22,195
No. l won't do it.

975
01:17:22,603 --> 01:17:25,401
l'm not a politician.
l'm not going to London.

976
01:17:25,643 --> 01:17:28,203
You're the strongest card we have.

977
01:17:29,403 --> 01:17:32,634
They call me an assassin and a murderer!

978
01:17:32,843 --> 01:17:35,073
Will Churchill even shake my hand?

979
01:17:35,243 --> 01:17:38,201
We've broached it and had no objections.

980
01:17:38,683 --> 01:17:40,036
You go, Dev.

981
01:17:40,163 --> 01:17:41,960
You're the statesman.

982
01:17:42,083 --> 01:17:45,120
You know how far we can push them.
They know you.

983
01:17:45,323 --> 01:17:48,440
That's the point. They don't know you.

984
01:17:53,683 --> 01:17:56,117
Don't do this to me, Dev. Don't do it.

985
01:17:56,923 --> 01:18:00,199
l'm no good at talk.
l'm a yob from West Cork.

986
01:18:00,323 --> 01:18:01,438
Please!

987
01:18:01,643 --> 01:18:04,760
You'll head our team, Michael...

988
01:18:05,883 --> 01:18:09,558
...to negotiate a treaty
for the first time in history...

989
01:18:09,723 --> 01:18:11,918
...between lreland and England.

990
01:18:14,043 --> 01:18:17,592
We need to keep
a final arbitrator in reserve.

991
01:18:17,763 --> 01:18:18,832
You.

992
01:18:19,523 --> 01:18:22,674
That will be the lrish people.

993
01:18:25,083 --> 01:18:26,516
And me...

994
01:18:27,003 --> 01:18:30,154
...as president of the lrish Republic.

995
01:18:31,563 --> 01:18:33,235
Why does he want me there?

996
01:18:33,323 --> 01:18:34,278
Why?

997
01:18:34,443 --> 01:18:37,640
-You put the fear of God into them.
-Save me the bullshit.

998
01:18:37,763 --> 01:18:41,312
Mick, you are the strongest card we have.

999
01:18:42,203 --> 01:18:43,477
What's he up to?

1000
01:18:45,523 --> 01:18:47,559
-What are you talking about?
-l have one simple asset.

1001
01:18:47,643 --> 01:18:50,282
All these years,
no one knows what l look like.

1002
01:18:59,323 --> 01:19:01,314
Which one of you is Michael Collins?

1003
01:19:01,403 --> 01:19:02,518
He is.

1004
01:19:03,403 --> 01:19:04,518
That's him.

1005
01:19:05,323 --> 01:19:06,642
The small fella.

1006
01:19:21,883 --> 01:19:26,195
'From your very own plenipotentiary,
to the provisions of the said document...

1007
01:19:26,363 --> 01:19:29,673
'...hereinafter to be referred to
as The Letter:

1008
01:19:30,563 --> 01:19:32,679
'They didn't defeat us by force of arms...

1009
01:19:32,763 --> 01:19:35,800
'...but now they'll try to
do it by force of verbiage.

1010
01:19:35,963 --> 01:19:39,114
'The English language wasn't
meant to be spoken like that.

1011
01:19:39,203 --> 01:19:42,513
'How did these people ever
get to run an empire?'

1012
01:19:49,403 --> 01:19:50,438
Don't.

1013
01:19:51,163 --> 01:19:52,278
Why not?

1014
01:19:53,683 --> 01:19:55,321
'Cause you'll get hurt.

1015
01:19:56,523 --> 01:19:57,956
How will l get hurt?

1016
01:20:04,123 --> 01:20:05,636
l'm in love with him.

1017
01:20:12,283 --> 01:20:13,557
l'm sorry.

1018
01:20:14,203 --> 01:20:15,761
l have to tell you.

1019
01:20:20,523 --> 01:20:21,956
Have you told him?

1020
01:20:25,083 --> 01:20:26,038
No.

1021
01:20:28,843 --> 01:20:30,435
And maybe l never will.

1022
01:20:33,403 --> 01:20:35,997
l'm only telling you
because l can't hurt you.

1023
01:20:43,883 --> 01:20:45,157
Lucky Mick.

1024
01:21:07,563 --> 01:21:10,999
I did my best, Kitty,
but it won't be good enough.

1025
01:21:13,563 --> 01:21:16,521
We'll have an Irish Free State,
instead of an Irish Republic.

1026
01:21:16,603 --> 01:21:18,514
We'll have our own government.

1027
01:21:18,843 --> 01:21:21,801
But we have to swear allegiance
to the English Crown.

1028
01:21:22,203 --> 01:21:24,194
The position of the
north will be reviewed...

1029
01:21:24,283 --> 01:21:27,320
...but now it remains part
of the British Empire.

1030
01:21:27,563 --> 01:21:29,872
This treaty isjust a steppingstone.

1031
01:21:30,043 --> 01:21:32,273
I hope the country sees it as such.

1032
01:21:34,123 --> 01:21:35,272
How are you?

1033
01:21:38,843 --> 01:21:40,913
ls this true?

1034
01:21:45,003 --> 01:21:47,153
lt's the best anyone could have got.

1035
01:21:48,843 --> 01:21:50,561
This gives up the north...

1036
01:21:51,083 --> 01:21:52,721
...divides the country.

1037
01:21:53,083 --> 01:21:56,678
You expect us to give an oath
of allegiance to the Crown?

1038
01:21:56,843 --> 01:21:59,403
They can't comprehend
giving us the Republic.

1039
01:21:59,563 --> 01:22:01,554
And that's why Dev sent me.

1040
01:22:02,683 --> 01:22:03,638
What?

1041
01:22:03,803 --> 01:22:05,873
He knew we'd get no Republic.

1042
01:22:06,043 --> 01:22:08,511
He wanted me to bring back the bad news.

1043
01:22:08,923 --> 01:22:13,474
We can use the lrish Free State
to achieve the Republic we want.

1044
01:22:13,643 --> 01:22:15,395
lt's either this or war.

1045
01:22:15,643 --> 01:22:18,111
l won't go to war over words.

1046
01:22:19,323 --> 01:22:21,962
What if it's war either way, Mick?

1047
01:22:23,563 --> 01:22:27,476
You published the terms
without my agreement!

1048
01:22:28,603 --> 01:22:31,401
-They were the best we could get.
-ln your opinion!

1049
01:22:31,483 --> 01:22:35,237
You sent me there knowing
they were the best we'd get.

1050
01:22:35,723 --> 01:22:37,953
-ldle speculation.
-No, it's the truth.

1051
01:22:38,043 --> 01:22:40,113
Or else you'd have gone yourself.

1052
01:22:40,283 --> 01:22:42,035
We don't have the Republic...

1053
01:22:42,123 --> 01:22:45,240
...but freedom to achieve it.
Peacefully.

1054
01:22:45,403 --> 01:22:47,553
Surely it's time for peace.

1055
01:22:48,923 --> 01:22:51,881
What would you know about peace?

1056
01:22:56,443 --> 01:22:59,913
You said we could negotiate
on behalf of our government...

1057
01:23:00,123 --> 01:23:02,921
...the D il and the lrish people.

1058
01:23:04,283 --> 01:23:06,353
lf they reject it, l'll reject it.

1059
01:23:06,643 --> 01:23:09,521
lf they stand by it, l'll stand by it.

1060
01:23:09,883 --> 01:23:11,953
l want to know you'll do the same.

1061
01:24:01,243 --> 01:24:03,074
Will you come in for a pint?

1062
01:24:25,003 --> 01:24:26,516
He's read the papers.

1063
01:24:42,643 --> 01:24:44,440
Say something, would you?

1064
01:24:48,283 --> 01:24:51,002
l've known the two of you for four years.

1065
01:24:52,443 --> 01:24:56,197
You've slept together,
lived together, fought together.

1066
01:24:57,803 --> 01:24:59,475
But your war is over now.

1067
01:25:03,083 --> 01:25:05,074
What if it's just the beginning?

1068
01:25:08,123 --> 01:25:09,078
Christ.

1069
01:25:09,243 --> 01:25:11,154
l'd be better off in Longford.

1070
01:25:46,083 --> 01:25:48,517
We were elected by the people of lreland...

1071
01:25:48,603 --> 01:25:50,514
We were elected by the people.

1072
01:25:50,723 --> 01:25:55,080
Did they think we were liars when we
meant to uphold the lrish Republic?

1073
01:25:57,323 --> 01:26:00,713
The letters preceding the negotiations...

1074
01:26:00,923 --> 01:26:04,552
...not once demanded recognition
of the lrish Republic!

1075
01:26:05,003 --> 01:26:07,995
We knew it would have been refused!

1076
01:26:08,283 --> 01:26:10,319
So Mr. Collins is asking us...

1077
01:26:10,523 --> 01:26:13,754
...to accept an oath of allegiance
to a foreign king...

1078
01:26:14,123 --> 01:26:15,761
...and the partition...

1079
01:26:16,803 --> 01:26:19,920
...and the partition of the northern part
of the country!

1080
01:26:20,283 --> 01:26:23,719
Mr. Collins,
the man who won the recent war...

1081
01:26:25,643 --> 01:26:27,873
...has himself described the treaty...

1082
01:26:28,043 --> 01:26:30,841
...as a steppingstone toward
the ultimate freedom!

1083
01:26:32,843 --> 01:26:37,553
Mr. Griffith has described Mr. Collins
as the man who won the war!

1084
01:26:41,963 --> 01:26:43,794
Point of order, Mr. Chairman.

1085
01:26:43,923 --> 01:26:46,039
Are we discussing the treaty or myself?

1086
01:26:46,123 --> 01:26:48,114
The minister does not like what l say!

1087
01:26:48,203 --> 01:26:49,875
Anything about me, say it!

1088
01:26:49,963 --> 01:26:52,523
Mr. Collins, your position in the army...

1089
01:26:52,683 --> 01:26:55,402
...was as chief of one subsection.

1090
01:26:58,283 --> 01:27:00,672
Nobody sought notoriety except you!

1091
01:27:00,803 --> 01:27:02,521
Come on, Cathal!

1092
01:27:02,643 --> 01:27:05,999
One person was held up by the press...

1093
01:27:06,203 --> 01:27:08,842
...and put into a position he never held.

1094
01:27:09,083 --> 01:27:12,041
He was made a romantic figure...

1095
01:27:14,083 --> 01:27:15,994
...a mystical character...

1096
01:27:16,083 --> 01:27:17,880
...which he certainly is not!

1097
01:27:17,963 --> 01:27:21,114
The person l refer to is Michael Collins!

1098
01:27:34,403 --> 01:27:36,314
l would plead...

1099
01:27:37,203 --> 01:27:38,921
...with every person here.

1100
01:27:39,963 --> 01:27:43,797
Make me a scapegoat, if you will.
Call me a traitor, if you will.

1101
01:27:44,683 --> 01:27:47,402
But please, let's save the country.

1102
01:27:48,203 --> 01:27:51,115
The alternative to this treaty is a war...

1103
01:27:51,763 --> 01:27:55,153
...which nobody in this gathering
can even contemplate.

1104
01:27:56,123 --> 01:27:57,761
lf the price of freedom...

1105
01:27:57,843 --> 01:28:00,482
...the price of peace,
is blackening my name...

1106
01:28:01,283 --> 01:28:03,001
...l will gladly pay it.

1107
01:28:06,003 --> 01:28:07,038
Thank you.

1108
01:28:25,803 --> 01:28:28,158
The result, ladies and gentlemen...

1109
01:28:28,323 --> 01:28:30,439
...is 64 to 57.

1110
01:28:31,883 --> 01:28:33,794
A majority of seven...

1111
01:28:35,843 --> 01:28:37,674
...in favor of the treaty.

1112
01:28:55,043 --> 01:28:58,399
There is one thing l want to say.

1113
01:29:03,243 --> 01:29:04,801
l want it to go...

1114
01:29:05,883 --> 01:29:07,794
...to the country...

1115
01:29:08,483 --> 01:29:10,678
...and to the world.

1116
01:29:13,003 --> 01:29:14,595
And it is this:

1117
01:29:17,203 --> 01:29:20,878
The lrish people established the Republic.

1118
01:29:22,963 --> 01:29:24,521
lt can only...

1119
01:29:24,723 --> 01:29:27,237
...be disestablished...

1120
01:29:27,403 --> 01:29:29,519
...by the lrish people.

1121
01:29:36,843 --> 01:29:38,640
As a protest...

1122
01:29:39,203 --> 01:29:42,354
...against the ratification of this treaty...

1123
01:29:42,483 --> 01:29:44,838
...which can only subvert...

1124
01:29:44,963 --> 01:29:46,521
...the Republic...

1125
01:29:49,763 --> 01:29:50,718
...l...

1126
01:29:50,883 --> 01:29:53,477
...and my deputies...

1127
01:29:53,603 --> 01:29:56,037
...are leaving this house.

1128
01:30:13,403 --> 01:30:14,597
Traitors!

1129
01:30:14,723 --> 01:30:16,202
Traitors, all!

1130
01:30:26,523 --> 01:30:27,876
Not you, Harry.

1131
01:30:41,323 --> 01:30:42,836
All right, you've won.

1132
01:30:46,203 --> 01:30:48,592
You always win, Mr. Collins.

1133
01:30:49,363 --> 01:30:50,921
Rarely, Miss Kiernan.

1134
01:30:51,083 --> 01:30:52,516
Very rarely.

1135
01:30:54,083 --> 01:30:55,914
Jesus, l hate you.

1136
01:30:56,843 --> 01:30:58,879
Sure. Join the club.

1137
01:31:51,963 --> 01:31:54,193
You're seven minutes late, Mr. Collins.

1138
01:31:54,283 --> 01:31:56,399
You've kept us waiting 700 years.

1139
01:31:56,563 --> 01:31:58,554
You can have your seven minutes.

1140
01:31:58,923 --> 01:32:00,834
Let's get this over with.

1141
01:32:04,523 --> 01:32:06,912
Company, present arms!

1142
01:32:32,883 --> 01:32:35,636
So that's what caused all the bother?

1143
01:32:43,883 --> 01:32:44,998
Now what?

1144
01:32:46,483 --> 01:32:48,201
Do l get to wear that hat?

1145
01:32:54,363 --> 01:32:56,001
This treaty...

1146
01:32:56,403 --> 01:32:58,963
...bars the way to the Republic...

1147
01:33:00,523 --> 01:33:02,002
...with the blood...

1148
01:33:02,643 --> 01:33:04,520
...of fellow lrishmen!

1149
01:33:12,603 --> 01:33:14,912
lf it is only with civil war...

1150
01:33:16,323 --> 01:33:18,917
...that we can get our independence...

1151
01:33:19,723 --> 01:33:21,634
...then so be it!

1152
01:33:39,883 --> 01:33:41,794
The Volunteers...

1153
01:33:42,443 --> 01:33:45,560
...will have to wade through lrish blood...

1154
01:33:48,003 --> 01:33:52,281
...through the blood of some members
of this government...

1155
01:33:52,803 --> 01:33:55,237
...in order to get...

1156
01:33:55,603 --> 01:33:57,434
...lrish freedom!

1157
01:34:03,003 --> 01:34:05,198
After 700 years....

1158
01:34:05,403 --> 01:34:07,200
After 700 years....

1159
01:34:23,883 --> 01:34:25,157
Let him speak!

1160
01:34:25,283 --> 01:34:26,602
Kitty, don't!

1161
01:34:26,763 --> 01:34:28,037
Leave him be!

1162
01:34:29,803 --> 01:34:32,363
You put the heart across me, Kitty.

1163
01:34:32,523 --> 01:34:34,479
l like the sound of your voice.

1164
01:34:37,483 --> 01:34:39,360
They won't accept the treaty.

1165
01:34:39,563 --> 01:34:41,155
No matter how the vote goes.

1166
01:34:41,243 --> 01:34:43,154
You heard what de Valera said.

1167
01:34:45,803 --> 01:34:48,681
'And to wade through rivers of blood....'

1168
01:34:48,923 --> 01:34:51,118
And who's blood you think
he's talking about?

1169
01:34:51,203 --> 01:34:52,079
Yours.

1170
01:34:52,243 --> 01:34:53,642
Will you marry me?

1171
01:34:54,363 --> 01:34:55,318
Yeah.

1172
01:34:59,403 --> 01:35:00,438
You will?

1173
01:35:04,363 --> 01:35:05,876
lt's that simple?

1174
01:35:06,443 --> 01:35:07,398
Yeah.

1175
01:36:17,163 --> 01:36:19,233
Who gave you that, you little runt?

1176
01:36:21,243 --> 01:36:22,312
What's all this about?

1177
01:36:22,403 --> 01:36:24,598
-We've taken over the Four Courts.
-You fucking fool!

1178
01:36:24,683 --> 01:36:25,559
Mind your language.

1179
01:36:25,643 --> 01:36:27,281
You'll start a civil war!

1180
01:36:27,363 --> 01:36:28,955
We'll defend the Republic.

1181
01:36:29,043 --> 01:36:30,601
These kids don't know guns!

1182
01:36:30,683 --> 01:36:33,243
-We know how to train them.
-The way l trained you?

1183
01:36:33,323 --> 01:36:35,678
-On whose orders?
-The Volunteer Executive.

1184
01:36:35,763 --> 01:36:37,196
Dev's part of it?

1185
01:36:37,403 --> 01:36:38,631
His half of it?

1186
01:36:39,683 --> 01:36:42,436
Go away home to your mothers,
all of you!

1187
01:36:47,003 --> 01:36:48,641
You know what this means?

1188
01:36:48,723 --> 01:36:50,554
The army's split down the middle.

1189
01:36:50,643 --> 01:36:52,679
-Who's in there?
-Mellowes, Lynch...

1190
01:36:52,763 --> 01:36:54,594
...Tom Barry, Oscar Traynor.

1191
01:37:06,643 --> 01:37:08,042
Keep it off.

1192
01:37:08,763 --> 01:37:09,718
Why?

1193
01:37:09,843 --> 01:37:12,232
There's a gunman outside by the railings.

1194
01:37:12,723 --> 01:37:14,600
Jesus' sake.

1195
01:37:15,603 --> 01:37:17,321
They won't shoot me, then.

1196
01:37:20,403 --> 01:37:22,439
Jesus, what are you doing to me?

1197
01:37:23,403 --> 01:37:25,314
They can shoot us, but they can't get us.

1198
01:37:25,403 --> 01:37:27,598
-What are you talking about?
-lt's not possible.

1199
01:37:27,683 --> 01:37:29,753
l'm going to live to see you old.

1200
01:37:30,443 --> 01:37:31,876
l am old.

1201
01:37:32,643 --> 01:37:34,679
Old enough to see your hair turn grey.

1202
01:37:34,763 --> 01:37:36,993
l come from a long line of baldies.

1203
01:37:37,203 --> 01:37:38,238
Bald, then.

1204
01:37:38,323 --> 01:37:39,836
l can live with that.

1205
01:37:42,763 --> 01:37:46,961
l will not fight against men l trained with,
l fought with!

1206
01:37:47,163 --> 01:37:51,475
The people have spoken
for the treaty you brought home!

1207
01:37:51,603 --> 01:37:55,073
They've occupied the Four Courts,
Limerick, Cork. lt's anarchy.

1208
01:37:55,243 --> 01:37:56,801
Better anarchy than civil war!

1209
01:37:56,883 --> 01:38:00,193
-Churchill offered artillery!
-He can do his own dirty work!

1210
01:38:00,603 --> 01:38:02,241
Maybe he will, Michael.

1211
01:38:02,843 --> 01:38:04,037
Maybe he will.

1212
01:38:13,763 --> 01:38:14,639
Stop!

1213
01:38:14,803 --> 01:38:16,919
-lt's not safe--
-Do as you're told.

1214
01:38:29,883 --> 01:38:32,397
Harry, talk to me, will you?

1215
01:38:32,843 --> 01:38:34,196
l don't want any bullshit, Mick.

1216
01:38:34,283 --> 01:38:35,557
Neither do l.

1217
01:38:38,163 --> 01:38:39,596
Come upstairs.

1218
01:38:51,363 --> 01:38:53,001
ls it true what l heard?

1219
01:38:54,443 --> 01:38:55,796
You're engaged?

1220
01:38:56,843 --> 01:38:58,879
Should l apologize for that, too?

1221
01:38:59,843 --> 01:39:01,162
No, no, no.

1222
01:39:01,563 --> 01:39:03,201
l'm happy for you both.

1223
01:39:03,323 --> 01:39:05,075
Me arse. You don't look it.

1224
01:39:05,163 --> 01:39:07,677
Maybe l don't, but l'm trying.

1225
01:39:08,483 --> 01:39:10,678
Do you understand? l'm trying.

1226
01:39:19,723 --> 01:39:21,634
l miss the way it used to be.

1227
01:39:23,163 --> 01:39:24,232
Me too.

1228
01:39:26,443 --> 01:39:28,638
l hear you're Dev's right-hand man.

1229
01:39:29,883 --> 01:39:32,397
Well, l suppose that's how it goes.

1230
01:39:33,963 --> 01:39:35,874
We were too dangerous together.

1231
01:39:39,603 --> 01:39:41,480
Know the funny thing, Harry?

1232
01:39:44,363 --> 01:39:46,797
For the first time in my life, l'm scared.

1233
01:39:50,363 --> 01:39:52,194
The Big Fella, scared?

1234
01:39:54,363 --> 01:39:57,594
l hate to say it, Mick,
but you've a right to be.

1235
01:39:58,763 --> 01:40:00,401
You don't understand me.

1236
01:40:02,043 --> 01:40:04,557
You told me once
l was good at bloody mayhem.

1237
01:40:04,843 --> 01:40:05,798
Right.

1238
01:40:05,963 --> 01:40:07,635
l left the Brits in the halfpenny place.

1239
01:40:07,723 --> 01:40:10,362
That's what l'm scared of,
because once l start...

1240
01:40:10,443 --> 01:40:11,717
...there'll be no stopping me.

1241
01:40:14,803 --> 01:40:17,601
Don't let it start, then.

1242
01:40:18,003 --> 01:40:19,436
Tear up that treaty.

1243
01:40:23,523 --> 01:40:25,434
lt's the only thing we've got.

1244
01:40:27,203 --> 01:40:29,034
So, then it starts.

1245
01:40:29,203 --> 01:40:30,158
What?

1246
01:40:31,443 --> 01:40:32,956
We fight.

1247
01:40:34,603 --> 01:40:36,355
They fight. We don't.

1248
01:40:36,523 --> 01:40:39,162
You've said what you had to say
and you can go now.

1249
01:40:39,243 --> 01:40:41,757
Listen,
you don't know what you're saying!

1250
01:40:41,963 --> 01:40:44,352
l have nothing more to say to you!

1251
01:40:46,943 --> 01:40:48,740
-Do it!
-Put the gun down!

1252
01:40:48,943 --> 01:40:51,093
Save us all a lot of bother. Do it!

1253
01:40:51,383 --> 01:40:52,816
Put the gun down.

1254
01:40:55,383 --> 01:40:58,580
Do you not hear me!
l said put the gun down!

1255
01:41:01,663 --> 01:41:02,652
Get out!

1256
01:41:23,870 --> 01:41:25,622
-Do it!
-Fire!

1257
01:41:51,110 --> 01:41:53,226
How would you like a new boss, Joe?

1258
01:43:21,310 --> 01:43:22,789
Check the other side.

1259
01:43:29,990 --> 01:43:31,184
What happened?

1260
01:43:39,230 --> 01:43:42,745
They shot their way to the Catacombs.
He thinks Harry was with them.

1261
01:43:42,830 --> 01:43:44,980
-Let's go.
-Mick, it's not safe!

1262
01:43:45,150 --> 01:43:46,788
We'll never get through!

1263
01:44:14,910 --> 01:44:15,865
Stop!

1264
01:44:16,030 --> 01:44:17,099
Stop!

1265
01:44:43,910 --> 01:44:45,309
Come on! Come on!

1266
01:45:56,470 --> 01:45:58,938
Calm down! lt's the Big Fella!

1267
01:46:09,590 --> 01:46:10,784
What happened?

1268
01:46:12,990 --> 01:46:14,264
Who closed your eyes?

1269
01:46:14,350 --> 01:46:17,501
He tried to run across the river, sir.
l plugged him.

1270
01:46:17,670 --> 01:46:19,865
l didn't ask you. l asked him.

1271
01:46:20,230 --> 01:46:21,504
You asked who?

1272
01:46:21,670 --> 01:46:23,547
l fucking asked him!

1273
01:46:23,710 --> 01:46:26,383
-But he's dead, sir.
-And you killed him, you little git!

1274
01:46:26,470 --> 01:46:28,904
You plugged him,
you Free State gob-shite!

1275
01:46:29,510 --> 01:46:31,228
-You were meant to protect him!
-He was one of them, sir!

1276
01:46:31,310 --> 01:46:33,346
No, sonny! You don't understand.

1277
01:46:34,590 --> 01:46:36,148
He was one of us.

1278
01:46:37,750 --> 01:46:38,739
Go on!

1279
01:46:38,910 --> 01:46:40,787
Back to your posts.

1280
01:46:49,350 --> 01:46:52,228
The papers said his last words were:

1281
01:46:53,750 --> 01:46:55,820
'Have they got Mick Collins yet?'

1282
01:46:56,550 --> 01:46:58,427
You know it's not true, Mick.

1283
01:47:01,150 --> 01:47:03,710
l don't know anything, anymore.

1284
01:47:09,670 --> 01:47:12,787
Tell Dev Mick wants to talk.
Nothing more, nothing less.

1285
01:47:12,910 --> 01:47:14,309
Not in Dublin.

1286
01:47:14,470 --> 01:47:15,698
Where, then?

1287
01:47:15,830 --> 01:47:17,024
West Cork...

1288
01:47:17,990 --> 01:47:19,343
...there might be a chance.

1289
01:47:19,430 --> 01:47:21,500
He'd never get out of there alive.

1290
01:47:21,670 --> 01:47:23,023
Doesn't he come from there?

1291
01:47:23,110 --> 01:47:24,828
That's bandit country.

1292
01:47:24,990 --> 01:47:27,140
They're bandits he trained, aren't they?

1293
01:47:27,230 --> 01:47:29,664
Maybe.
But Mick doesn't know the new boys.

1294
01:47:30,390 --> 01:47:32,699
He'll have to get to know them now.

1295
01:47:35,390 --> 01:47:36,459
Gentlemen.

1296
01:47:59,550 --> 01:48:00,539
What time is it?

1297
01:48:00,630 --> 01:48:02,905
Seven. Have you been here all night?

1298
01:48:03,230 --> 01:48:04,219
Any news?

1299
01:48:04,310 --> 01:48:07,507
They say if you went to Cork
there might be a possibility.

1300
01:48:07,830 --> 01:48:08,706
Fuck!

1301
01:48:09,910 --> 01:48:11,184
What do you think?

1302
01:48:11,270 --> 01:48:15,104
We've cleared them out
except for West Cork.

1303
01:48:16,710 --> 01:48:19,144
They wouldn't kill me in my own county.

1304
01:48:21,670 --> 01:48:23,786
How would you like a new boss, Joe?

1305
01:48:25,190 --> 01:48:27,101
Still, be nice to go home.

1306
01:48:29,670 --> 01:48:31,979
-You'd be crazy to go.
-So, l'm crazy.

1307
01:48:32,150 --> 01:48:33,981
Get the convoy together.

1308
01:48:34,150 --> 01:48:35,219
Go on.

1309
01:48:43,150 --> 01:48:45,027
-What?
-Here. For the cough.

1310
01:48:45,670 --> 01:48:47,388
Here. New handkerchief.

1311
01:48:47,990 --> 01:48:51,824
Go on! You're like an old clucking hen,
fussing all the time!

1312
01:49:06,950 --> 01:49:08,463
Sweet suffering Jesus!

1313
01:49:08,550 --> 01:49:10,700
lf you're going down, l'm going too.

1314
01:49:28,070 --> 01:49:29,742
That's where it all started, Joe.

1315
01:49:29,830 --> 01:49:31,786
Fenian stories by the fireside.

1316
01:49:31,870 --> 01:49:33,144
That's your home?

1317
01:49:33,230 --> 01:49:35,061
Was, till the Tans burned it.

1318
01:49:40,750 --> 01:49:42,308
What are you doing here, Mick?

1319
01:49:42,390 --> 01:49:44,062
Haven't l a civil war to run?

1320
01:49:44,150 --> 01:49:45,788
Come on! lt's my round.

1321
01:49:57,990 --> 01:50:00,788
Come to flog us that bloody treaty,
have you?

1322
01:50:01,310 --> 01:50:03,301
l'm flogging fuck-all.
l've come to buy.

1323
01:50:03,390 --> 01:50:05,221
Drinks for the county on me.

1324
01:50:07,430 --> 01:50:09,022
Come on, four pints.

1325
01:50:35,230 --> 01:50:36,424
ls it him?

1326
01:50:38,070 --> 01:50:39,264
Looks like it.

1327
01:50:40,630 --> 01:50:42,461
Looks like he wants to meet.

1328
01:50:50,150 --> 01:50:51,822
Can l trust him?

1329
01:50:52,550 --> 01:50:54,859
Can you trust anyone these days, chief?

1330
01:51:17,190 --> 01:51:19,750
'Oh, well do l remember...

1331
01:51:20,230 --> 01:51:21,583
'...the year of '48

1332
01:51:21,750 --> 01:51:24,423
'When l rose with comrades
brave and true

1333
01:51:27,710 --> 01:51:30,224
'l was hunted through the hills by slaves

1334
01:51:30,390 --> 01:51:33,029
'Who served a foreign queen

1335
01:51:33,790 --> 01:51:34,779
''And that's

1336
01:51:34,870 --> 01:51:37,065
''Another reason why

1337
01:51:37,350 --> 01:51:39,818
''I left old Skibereen''

1338
01:51:49,590 --> 01:51:50,989
Say it to me, kid.

1339
01:51:51,070 --> 01:51:52,423
Put it away, Joe.

1340
01:51:52,790 --> 01:51:54,303
Who the fuck are you?

